Module:
 encapsulated code, you can ask for it and what you get back is only what it lets 
 you to have. It doesnot cause side effects.

Here how it is under the hood: 
var module1 = (function( exports, require, module, __filename, __dirname) {
    // your nodejs code in a file
});


==== Common JS ====

==== Creating Modules ====
All your nodejs code is already module 

exmample:
   const add = () => {}
   module.exports = add; // default export
   module.exports = {    //named exports 
       add, thing(),
       value: 1
   } 

   import : 
   const data = require('');

   there is only one module.exports statement if you write another one 
   you can overwrite the previous export.
   but you can append a new property usingh 
   module.exports.newProperty 

   =======